# ğŸ“š Algorithmic Toolkit (Mini Project 3)

This is a comprehensive **Java utility library** designed to consolidate common DSA (Data Structures & Algorithms) patterns into a single, reusable toolkit. It provides robust, easy-to-use classes for sorting, searching, fundamental collections, and algorithm performance benchmarking.

---

## ğŸš€ Core Toolkit Features

### Sorting Utilities (`SortingUtil`)
Provides implementations of popular sorting algorithms for integer arrays.

| Algorithm | Average Time Complexity | Notes |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Bubble Sort** | $O(n^2)$ | Simple, but inefficient for large datasets. |
| **Insertion Sort** | $O(n^2)$ | Efficient for small or mostly sorted arrays. |
| **Merge Sort** | $O(n \log n)$ | Stable and reliable, based on the Divide and Conquer principle. |
| **Quick Sort** | $O(n \log n)$ | Generally the fastest in practice; worst-case complexity is $O(n^2)$. |

### Searching Utilities (`SearchUtil`)
Provides essential search algorithms for locating elements within an array.
* **Linear Search** â€“ $O(n)$
* **Binary Search** â€“ $O(\log n)$ (Requires the input array to be sorted)

Methods return the index of the target element or **-1** if not found.

### Collection Utilities (`CollectionUtil`)
Provides generic implementations of fundamental data structures using Java collections:
* **Stack** â€“ Supports `push`, `pop`, `peek`, and `isEmpty`.
* **Queue** â€“ Supports `enqueue`, `dequeue`, `peek`, and `isEmpty`.

### Analysis Utilities (`AnalysisUtil`)
Measures the execution time of any given algorithm using the standard Java `Runnable` interface.
* Returns execution time in **nanoseconds** for precise benchmarking.

---

## ğŸ§© Project Structure

The utility classes are organized under a standard Java package structure:
AlgorithmToolkit/ â””â”€â”€ src/ â””â”€â”€ com/algorithmtoolkit/ (Java Package: com.algorithmtoolkit) â”œâ”€â”€ AnalysisUtil.java â”œâ”€â”€ CollectionUtil.java â”œâ”€â”€ SearchUtil.java â”œâ”€â”€ SortingUtil.java â””â”€â”€ TestMain.java (Main entry point for demonstrations and testing)
## â–¶ï¸ How to Run (IntelliJ IDEA)

1.  **Clone** or download the project files.
2.  Open the project directory in **IntelliJ IDEA**.
3.  Ensure the JDK is configured (JDK 21 was used for development).
4.  Right-click on **`TestMain.java`** in the `com.algorithmtoolkit` package and select **Run**.
5.  Observe the results, timing data, and data structure operations in the console output.

